# =============================================================================
# Claude Code (and other Anthropic-compatible clients) — Configuration Template
# =============================================================================
#
# This wrapper exposes NVIDIA NIM as a CUSTOM provider for Claude Code. Two
# layers of configuration matter:
#
#   (A) WRAPPER-SIDE  — variables the wrapper reads (set in this file / .env).
#   (B) CLIENT-SIDE   — variables Claude Code itself reads (set in the user's
#                       shell / claude config). Capability declaration is
#                       CLIENT-SIDE: the gateway cannot auto-detect a model's
#                       thinking/effort support from any API response, so the
#                       client MUST declare it. The companion _SUPPORTED_
#                       CAPABILITIES vars below are read by Claude Code, not
#                       by this wrapper.
#
# -----------------------------------------------------------------------------
# (A) WRAPPER-SIDE — alias mapping (Claude Code built-in family aliases)
# -----------------------------------------------------------------------------
# Claude Code sends built-in family aliases (haiku / sonnet / opus) for
# background tasks and subagents even when a custom model is pinned. NIM 404s
# those aliases unless we map them to real NIM models. Set these to the NIM
# model ids you actually want behind each family. These are required for the
# gateway to serve Claude Code without silent fallback / 4xx errors.
#
CLAUDE_CODE_DEFAULT_HAIKU_MODEL=meta/llama-3.1-8b-instruct
CLAUDE_CODE_DEFAULT_SONNET_MODEL=deepseek-ai/deepseek-v4-pro
CLAUDE_CODE_DEFAULT_OPUS_MODEL=nvidia/nemotron-3-ultra-550b-a55b
#
# (Compatibility aliases also accepted: ANTHROPIC_DEFAULT_HAIKU_MODEL, etc.)
#
# Arbitrary extra aliases (JSON object: "client-alias" -> "owner/model").
# Useful to pin a custom model name exposed in /v1/models discovery.
# ANTHROPIC_ALIAS_MAP={"my-team-model":"deepseek-ai/deepseek-v4-flash"}
#
# -----------------------------------------------------------------------------
# (B) CLIENT-SIDE — what the USER puts in their Claude Code environment
# -----------------------------------------------------------------------------
# 1) Enable gateway model discovery so the wrapper's models appear in the
#    /model picker. Claude Code ONLY lists ids that begin with "claude" or
#    "anthropic" — the wrapper already aliases every NIM id to a claude-* id
#    in GET /v1/models, so this is what makes them show up:
#
#      export CLAUDE_CODE_ENABLE_GATEWAY_MODEL_DISCOVERY=1
#
# 2) Point Claude Code at the wrapper as a custom Anthropic gateway:
#
#      export ANTHROPIC_BASE_URL=http://<wrapper-host>:9100
#      export ANTHROPIC_AUTH_TOKEN=wrapper-local-key   # MUST match BEARER_TOKEN
#                                                     # in the wrapper's .env
#                                                     # (default in production: same value).
#                                                     # The wrapper validates the
#                                                     # token on every non-public
#                                                     # endpoint — sending a non-
#                                                     # matching value yields 401.
#
# 3) Pin the default model (raw NIM id works; the wrapper passes it through,
#    or use the claude-* discovery id from GET /v1/models):
#
#      export ANTHROPIC_MODEL=deepseek-ai/deepseek-v4-pro
#
# 4) Per-agent model pins (background / subagent tasks). These are what stop
#    Claude Code from sending the bare "haiku/sonnet/opus" aliases that NIM
#    would 404 — the wrapper maps them too, but pinning here is cleaner:
#
#      export ANTHROPIC_DEFAULT_HAIKU_MODEL=meta/llama-3.1-8b-instruct
#      export ANTHROPIC_DEFAULT_SONNET_MODEL=deepseek-ai/deepseek-v4-pro
#      export ANTHROPIC_DEFAULT_OPUS_MODEL=nvidia/nemotron-3-ultra-550b-a55b
#      export CLAUDE_CODE_SUBAGENT_MODEL=deepseek-ai/deepseek-v4-flash
#
# 5) Capability declaration (CLIENT-SIDE, required for thinking/effort to
#    work). Claude Code reads these to know what the model behind the gateway
#    supports. Comma-separated list of supported capability tokens:
#
#      export ANTHROPIC_CUSTOM_MODEL_OPTION_supports_thinking=true
#      export ANTHROPIC_CUSTOM_MODEL_OPTION_supports_extended_thinking=true
#      export ANTHROPIC_CUSTOM_MODEL_OPTION_supports_interleaved_thinking=true
#      export ANTHROPIC_CUSTOM_MODEL_OPTION_supports_adaptive_thinking=true
#      export ANTHROPIC_CUSTOM_MODEL_OPTION_supports_effort=true
#      export ANTHROPIC_CUSTOM_MODEL_OPTION_supports_xhigh_effort=true
#
#    Per-model capability can be declared with the
#    ANTHROPIC_CUSTOM_MODEL_OPTION_<model>_SUPPORTED_CAPABILITIES form, e.g.:
#
#      export ANTHROPIC_CUSTOM_MODEL_OPTION_deepseek-v4-pro_SUPPORTED_CAPABILITIES="thinking,effort,interleaved_thinking,adaptive_thinking,xhigh_effort"
#      export ANTHROPIC_CUSTOM_MODEL_OPTION_meta-llama-3.1-8b-instruct_SUPPORTED_CAPABILITIES=""
#
#    The wrapper also advertises static capability flags (supports_*,
#    context_window, max_output_tokens) in GET /v1/models and GET
#    /v1/capabilities, but the authoritative extended-thinking/effort
#    declaration is client-side as above. Context window with a [1m] suffix
#    (e.g. a discovery id like claude-deepseek-v4-pro[1m]) is stripped by the
#    wrapper before routing.
#
# -----------------------------------------------------------------------------
# NOTE: Other OpenAI-compatible clients (OpenCode, Hermes, Kilo Code, OpenClaw)
# simply point base_url at http://<wrapper-host>:9910/v1 and send raw NIM ids
# (transparent pass-through). No per-client special-casing is needed — the
# wrapper speaks standard OpenAI Chat Completions and Anthropic Messages API.
# =============================================================================
